<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="34" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[136,1452,1022,1661]" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,519,1310,1336]" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Distribution and ecology:—</emphasis>
The species is endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[812,883,1310,1336]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, with records in the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[1207,1275,1310,1336]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Bahia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1285,1448,1310,1336]" country="Brazil" name="Espirito Santo" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Espírito Santo</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[136,287,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="Minas Gerais" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Minas Gerais</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[297,458,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[467,581,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[590,666,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="Parana" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Paraná</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[717,880,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="Santa Catarina" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Santa Catarina</collectingRegion>
associated with the Cerrado and Atlantic Rainforest domains in areas of ombrophilous and seasonal forest (
<bibRefCitation author="Tozzi, A. M. G. A." box="[752,883,1382,1408]" pageId="17" pageNumber="34" pagination="22 - 83" refId="ref19233" refString="Tozzi, A. M. G. A. (2016) Subfamilia Caesalpinioideae. In: Tozzi, A., Melhem, T. S., Forero, E., Fortuna-Perez, A. P., Wanderley, M. G. L., Martins, S. E., Romanini, R. P., Pirani, J. R., Fiuza de Melo, M. M. R., Kirizawa, M., Yano &amp; Cordeiro, I. O. (Eds.) Flora Fanerogamica do Estado de Sao Paulo. Sao Paulo, pp. 22 - 83." type="book chapter" year="2016">Tozzi 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[136,1452,1022,1661]" box="[189,720,1418,1444]" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,351,1418,1444]" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Phenology:—</emphasis>
Registered with flowers in April.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[136,1452,1022,1661]" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,490,1454,1480]" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Taxonomic discussion:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. S. Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" box="[490,668,1454,1481]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Senna" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="17" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[490,668,1454,1481]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Senna angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized, mainly, by the shrub habit, 4-leaflet leaves and inflorescence in terminal raceme, with yellow corolla flowers, heterodinamous androecium, poricidal anthers and bacoid fruit. 
<taxonomicName box="[283,440,1526,1553]" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis box="[283,351,1527,1553]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Senna</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
found in the studied area have 4–leaflet leaves, except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Felder" authorityYear="1874" box="[1073,1239,1527,1553]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Senna" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="17" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="martina">
<emphasis box="[1073,1239,1527,1553]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Senna martina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. S. Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1753" box="[1295,1445,1526,1553]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Senna" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="17" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obtusifolia">
<emphasis box="[1295,1445,1526,1553]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">S. obtusifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which have a higher number of leaflets. Among the representatives of 
<taxonomicName box="[917,985,1562,1588]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Senna" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="17" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Senna</taxonomicName>
4–leaftles, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. S. Irwin &amp; Barneby" authorityYear="1982" box="[1115,1242,1562,1589]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Senna" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="17" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[1115,1242,1562,1589]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">S. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the one with the largest size, which can be confused with 
<taxonomicName box="[596,816,1598,1625]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Senna" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="17" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="macranthera">
<emphasis box="[596,816,1598,1625]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="34">Senna macranthera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the first is an erect shrub, while the second is a scandant shrub.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
